Selecting an Interrupt Handling Strategy

    This set of examples illustrates five different ways of handling the
    same interrupt (0xC or 0xB).  The purpose is to contrast the different
    methods, and to illustrate the minimum requirements for successfully
    installing a handler using each method.

    There are a number of generic issues which affect the selection of an 
    interrupt handling strategy.  In general, during the execution of a
    protected-mode program, interrupts may be signaled either in protected
    mode or in real mode.  This is because protected-mode programs spend
    some time in real mode when using DOS and BIOS services.  Mode switches
    cost time; for applications such as high-speed communications,
    minimizing the number of mode switches per interrupt can be a major
    consideration.  This isn't the case for most applications.  Usually,
    interrupts should be handled in the same way whether they are signaled
    in real mode or protected mode, and in this case having a single
    handler routine which is called in both cases is desireable.
    Occasionally, interrupts signaled in real mode need to be handled
    differently than those signaled in protected mode, and in that case
    separate, or specially configured dual-mode handlers will be needed.

    Interrupt handlers running in protected mode are easy to install and
    can access extended memory, including the data of the parent protected-
    mode program.  Interrupt handlers running in real mode are harder to
    install and invoke: their code and any data structures must be moved to
    low memory, and any addresses passed to them must be real-mode
    addresses.  They cannot access extended memory, and it is very
    difficult for the parent protected-mode program to pass data to them.
    This is because the DS register will point to the real-mode data
    segment of whatever real-mode program was active when the interrupt was
    signaled, not to the protected-mode parent program's data (or even to
    the interupt handler's own data).

    A final generic issue concerns DPMI.  In DPMI environments, the
    protected-mode interrupt handler is signaled first, no matter how you
    install the handlers.  This is a function of the DPMI host; the DOS/4G
    kernel has no control over this behavior.  As a result, the example
    programs behave very differently under DPMI than they do in other 
    environments: only the protected-mode interrupt handler will be
    signaled under DPMI, and in effect the interrupts will always be
    passup.  A DPMI host may also seriously interfere with BIOS behavior on
    which the example programs rely for timing functions, resulting in
    greatly altered output.  Your TSRs may be similarly affected.

    Detailed descriptions of the advantages and disadvantages of each of
    the interrupt handling strategies can be found in the comments for the
    HANDLERC.C source file.  Each of the five examples produce similar
    output: a row of letters is displayed across the screen by the
    interrupt handlers in response to interrupts signalled in real mode
    and/or in protected mode.  If the handler is running in real mode, the
    letters are red Rs, and if the handler is running in protected mode,
    they are purple Ps.  For cases where the original interrupt handler for
    that mode was not replaced, no letter at all is printed.  This allows
    you to see how each of the five strategies handles each kind of
    interrupt.

    The example consists of the following files in the EXAMPLES\HANDLERC
    directory:

    HANDLERC.C    C source file for examples of all five ways of installing
                  interrupt handlers.
                  
    HNDLINT.C     C source file for interrupt handlers and support
                  functions.

    HNDLINT.ASM   ASM source file for Microsoft interrupt handlers and 
    					support functions.

    BMRMHAND.ASM  Assembly source file for real-mode and bimodal-same
                  interrupt handlers.
                  
    HANDLERC.H    Include file used in building the example..

    MAKEFILE      Polymake-configured makefile for creating HANDLERC.EXE
                  using either Microsoft VC 4.x and/or Watcom.
